We need a root-level refinement of the StoryMath visual and copy system. Do not treat this as a cosmetic cleanup or solve it with display:none patches. Inspect the relevant lesson, equation-builder, feedback, visualization, and content-data components first, then refactor the rendering and copy architecture so these problems do not recur in future stories.

The current UI is over-carded, over-labeled, and full of redundant AI-style narration. It feels like generic educational SaaS scaffolding around a good model-building interaction. Preserve the calm typography, whitespace, native HTML/CSS/SVG approach, and underlying game mechanics, but simplify the hierarchy radically.

PRIMARY DESIGN PRINCIPLE:
Show the story once, the task once, and the mathematical relationship once. Every other visible element must earn its space.

CARD POLICY:
- Remove the large rounded outer lesson card/panel. The page itself is the canvas.
- Static reading content should not be inside cards, boxes, or pills.
- Surface follows action: only interactive objects such as quantity tiles, drop targets, operation buttons, and primary actions may use clear boundaries or backgrounds.
- Do not use nested cards, double-pill tags, decorative badges, or framed containers merely to create visual structure.
- Use typography, whitespace, alignment, and small dividers before adding boxes or borders.

REMOVE FROM CHILD-FACING UI:
- “Change Engine”
- the fictionalized/inspired-by disclaimer pill
- “A Different Question”
- “Multiplication creates a repeated-group question”
- “Tuesday distance runs far past this scale”
- “Let’s build it and see what the numbers say”
- “You can always revise”
- “Experimenting is good thinking”
- other generic narration that announces what the interaction already demonstrates

APP HEADER:
- Use “StoryMath” as the product identity only.
- Keep the current problem title visible.
- Replace decorative progress dots with plain text such as:
  “1 of 2 · Find Tuesday’s distance”
- Do not show “Change Engine” in the child-facing product.

STORY CONTENT:
- Put concrete context in one canonical narrative field, not in badges, metadata, and sentence fragments repeated across the screen.
- The story itself should include NASA, Mars, Perseverance, mission, place, goal, conflict, causal reason, and numerical change.
- For this problem, use this exact narrative:
  “NASA’s Mars rover Perseverance was mapping pale layers of rock near an ancient Martian river delta. It drove 384 meters on Monday. Overnight, one wheel slipped into soft sand, so on Tuesday it drove 128 fewer meters while engineers chose a safer path.”
- Provide thorough and comprehensive context within the word prompt itself, not fragmented meta tags. E.g. "NASA" "Mars Rover" "Perseverance" The full story details and background in one concrete, but simple text with clear relationships.
- Do not show a fictionalization/disclaimer label during the child lesson flow. If needed, preserve it only as non-default author/parent metadata.

ONE QUESTION PER PAGE:
- Step 1 asks only: “How far did Perseverance travel on Tuesday?”
- Do not mention the two-day total until the child completes Step 1.
- Step 2 asks only: “How far did Perseverance travel over both days?”
- The user should never be asked to hold two unknowns in working memory at the same time.

PREDICTION SCREEN:
- Replace the stacked heading/banner/question treatment with one prompt:
  “After the wheel slipped, how did Tuesday’s distance change?”
- Show choices: Farther / Shorter / The same.
- Once a choice is made, show only:
  “Your prediction: farther.”
- Do not add motivational or explanatory prose around this status.

QUANTITY TILE RULES:
- Remove duplicate inner tags such as “distance traveled” and “on Monday.”
- Each tile should be a coherent, concise object:
  “Monday distance” / “384 m”
  “Tuesday was shorter by” / “128 m”
- Avoid fragmented metadata pills.
- Quantity labels must not repeat the full story sentence.

EQUATION BUILDER:
- Make the builder a single connected working line, not three visually disconnected stacks of cards:
  [ Monday: 384 m ] [ operator ] [ shorter by: 128 m ] = [ Tuesday: ? ]
- Before values are placed, use subtle slots or dashed underlines.
- Once values are placed, use ordinary readable inline elements.
- Do not default to abstract labels such as “BIGGER AMOUNT,” “AMOUNT OF DIFFERENCE,” and “SMALLER AMOUNT.” These may exist as optional hints, but should not dominate the default screen.
- Use tap-to-place as a first-class interaction, with drag-and-drop optional rather than required.

VISUALIZATION ARCHITECTURE:
- Do not force every operation into the same bar-chart treatment.
- The equation data must be the single source of truth for every visualization.
- For addition/subtraction with comparable magnitudes, use an aligned linear SVG bar model.
- For multiplication with a large scale jump, use a repeated-groups model, not a fake bar comparison.
- For division, use an equal-sharing/equal-groups model.
- Never normalize two very different values into visually similar bars.
- Never use a misleading scale or silently truncate a value.
- Do not explain scale problems with visible prose such as “runs far past this scale.” Choose the correct visual model instead.

MULTIPLICATION PREVIEW:
When the learner chooses multiplication for the current Perseverance problem:
- Show this equation as the main statement:
  “384 × 128 = 49,152 meters”
- On the same line or immediately beside it, show:
  “That’s much farther than Monday.”
- Use a repeated-groups visual expressing “128 copies of one 384-meter drive,” not a mismatched bar chart.
- Replace the current explanatory block with exactly this alternate-world sentence:
  “This equation would fit a different story: if Perseverance drove Monday’s 384 meters on 128 different days, how far would it travel altogether?”
- Do not use generic labels such as “A Different Question” or “When multiplication fits.”

COPY GOVERNANCE:
- Every child-facing sentence must come from a curated story field or a small, intentional preview template.
- Do not concatenate arbitrary labels into generated narration.
- Do not generate explanatory text merely because a component has metadata available.
- If a phrase can be removed without impairing the child’s next action or understanding, remove it.
- Never repeat the same fact in the title, story, badge, card label, and feedback area.

PERSISTENCE:
- Add a concise “Child-facing UI and copy rules” section to CLAUDE.md or the appropriate project design document so future implementation work follows these constraints.
- After implementation, provide a concise list of changed files and verify each requirement above against the Perseverance flow.
